        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"671004\">@Danilo Krummrich</span> <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"519727\">@Alice Ryhl</span></p>\n<p>Hi both, following up on the mailing list discussion about v4 of the Vec shrink methods series (<a href=\"https://lore.kernel.org/rust-for-linux/20260207-binder-shrink-vec-v3-v3-0-8ff388563427@cock.li/\">thread</a>).</p>\n<p>I understand the agreed direction is to only provide <code>shrink_to()</code> for <code>VVec</code> and <code>KVVec</code>, not <code>KVec</code>. Just want to confirm my understanding of how to implement this:</p>\n<p>Since <code>VVec</code> and <code>KVVec</code> are type aliases:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">VVec</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Vec</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Vmalloc</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n<span class=\"k\">pub</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">type</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nc\">KVVec</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Vec</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">KVmalloc</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"p\">;</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Implementing <code>shrink_to()</code> on \"only VVec and KVVec\" means writing separate concrete impl blocks:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Rust\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Vec</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Vmalloc</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">shrink_to</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n<span class=\"k\">impl</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nb\">Vec</span><span class=\"o\">&lt;</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"p\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">KVmalloc</span><span class=\"o\">&gt;</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">fn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"nf\">shrink_to</span><span class=\"p\">()</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">{</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">..</span><span class=\"p\">.</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"p\">}</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Is that what you had in mind, with the shrink logic duplicated in both? Or would you prefer a shared impl with a trait bound to avoid the duplication?</p>\n<p>(Apologies for using Zulip - my email quota ran out again. Will follow up on the mailing list once it resets.)</p>",
        "id": 573183775,
        "sender_full_name": "shivamklr",
        "timestamp": 1770774116
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>We have no user for it on <code>VVec</code>, so we can just add it to <code>KVmalloc</code> and then generalize it to all allocators when we fix realloc in C.</p>",
